⛺️ Sleep system: tent, footprint, sleeping bag, sleeping pad, pillow, (optional liner)

💧 Water system: water filter/purifier, bottle(s)/bladder

🔦 Electronics: navi/inReach, power bank, cords, headlamp, batteries, camera, tripod

node.text:
My favorite freeze dried and/or dehydrated meals for backpacking and overnight climbing trips (swipe for pictures).

I’m not a backcountry chef, like at all. I’m pretty lazy after I hike or climb all day and the whole “just add boiling water to a bag” is a dream come true for someone like me who usually doesn’t want to cook or clean in the wilderness.

These are my five favorites!! I have celiac disease, therefore these are all GF. I’ve tried every single GF freeze dried and dehydrated meal I can possibly find and these are the best, IMO. Three of these are also vegan.

🍲 Chicken Pho, Good To Go
🍜 Pad Thai, Backpackers Pantry
🐖 Sweet Pork & Rice, Peak Refuel
🥥 Cuban Coconut Rice & Beans, BP Pantry
🍄 Mushroom Risotto, Good To Go

I eat both portions of the 2 servings meals because food is friend, especially after hiking/climbing after wearing a heavy pack all day.

The difference between freeze dried and dehydrated meals/ingredients👇🏻

🥶 Freeze dried = lighter w/ 98% water removed, reabsorbs water better/faster for better flavor/texture, maintains nutritional value, more expensive, can’t do at home

🥵 Dehydrated = a smidge heavier w/ 80% of water removed, water takes 20 minutes to reabsorb, loses some nutritional value, more affordable, can do at home

Most brands do a mix of freeze dried and dehydrated “fresh” ingredients to get the right taste for the right price.

Lastly, not all digestive tracts agree with these types of meals. So be sure to try one ahead of time to see how your body handles it if you’ve never had one before because you are new to backpacking!

node.text:
Rock climbing 🧗🏼‍♀️ the tallest mountain in the lower 48 was something that felt impossible to me a year ago. And here I am. Standing on top of the tallest mountain in the lower 48 on Tuesday with the LOML after climbing 11 pitches of sustained Sierra fifth class at 14k feet in the air.

From the moment we left camp at Iceberg Lake (12,500) at 6:30am, we worked as a team to stay on route up the East Buttress to the summit (14,505), then down climb the MR back to camp. I am SO proud of us/Ben for sending this climb, especially since it gave us the confidence to climb harder, longer alpine routes this summer and fall.

We didn’t tell many people we got the permit for this because I didn’t want to get told that we couldn’t handle this route given we’ve only been alpine climbing unguided for one year. We were 100% confident in our ability to handle over 1,000’ of exposed technical rock climbing at altitude together at our current skill and fitness level. And we fucking did it.

I love you so much @benharclerode!!

You make me feel so alive and the fact that you trust me as your climbing partner on these big climbs means so much to me!!

node.text:
“You can’t do that” is a very common reaction I get–almost always from straight white men–when I say I am going to do something, especially when it comes to climbing and mountaineering.

It’s always hard to tell if they think I’m actually incapable of whatever it is I have set out to do OR if their male egos are so threatened by it, they just *really* don’t want me to do it (or show women that you can do it too).

Either way, I let these words hold me back in climbing. I thought I had to adhere to the timelines these complete strangers on the internet put upon me. That maybe I couldn’t climb some of the objectives on my list as soon as planned.

“You can’t do it” almost became burned into my brain over the last 12 months since it’s been said to me so many times. I *almost* came to believe it. And it prevented me from sharing more of myself here out of fear of feeling like I “can’t” or am “not allowed” to climb certain routes or mountains “yet”.

Sharing less meant hearing those words less, which gave me some mental clarity. And as it turns out, I can climb many of the things men have told me that I “can’t”.

So I am all done accepting this phrase
And I am all done accepting these timelines

If you don’t think I’m capable, leave
If you don’t want me to climb rad shit, leave
If you don't want women to succeed, leave
✌🏻✌🏻✌🏻

“You can’t do that” is a phrase that will get you blocked moving forward and is no longer a phrase I will use for inspiration to get to a summit.

I climb for myself, my recovery, my marriage, and the people who love me, not for those who hate me and want me to fail. You don’t motivate me and nothing I do is for you.

Ben and I did something rad on Tuesday that I was keeping a secret out of fear of being told I/we couldn’t do it. And I am really excited to share in my next post (even though this photo totally gives it away).🧗🏼‍♀️

node.text:
This is someone who got so severely dehydrated, she had to emergency bivy at mile 30 in the dirt for the night. 10/10 would not recommend anything about this situation, as it was truly the opposite of fun… some real type-2.9 shit.

Three things caused this to happen:
1️⃣I didn’t hydrate anywhere near enough during travel the day/night before
2️⃣The heat zapped me and caused me to puke on our first and biggest day at 1pm
3️⃣I couldn’t catch up on fluids while pushing 35 miles + 12k feet of vert that day 
Miles 1-17 were lovely on every level and the stoke was high. Then I threw up—which is not abnormal for me—at a nice lake right after a ranger warned us about a washed out bridge and river crossing 13mi ahead.

It was around mile 20 that we started to get worried because the vomiting persisted and I started having a hard time regulating my body temperature. I was either sweating buckets or shivering (very bad sign).

By mile 25 we abandoned most hope of getting to camp 10mi ahead that day, but we kept moving because we knew we had to get as close as safely possible to shelter and food. I was still capable of walking at this point.

Miles 26-29 consisted of me repeatedly violently throwing up every ounce of water I drank, then laying in the fetal position on the trail dry crying. I was too dehydrated to shed tears. We decided that I was in no condition to cross the raging, waist deep river that night (smart thinking, go us).

By mile 29 I was begging Lyss to stop because my body was shutting down. She somehow calmly got me another mile downhill to water since we were out.

At 9pm and mile 30 we got my body to keep a half liter of electrolyte water down and decide it was time to stop moving before the river crossing. Lyss took her first emergency bivy experience like a fookin champ. It was cold and uncomfortable, but we did what had to be done.

We got moving at 5am, crossed the scary river, then climbed 4mi straight up to camp for our first real meal in 36 hours. It was the best meal I have ever had in my life.

My ego and my intuition argued with each other all day over getting back on the trail. My ego didn’t win this time!!

BE SAFE OUT THERE!!

node.text:
This is my favorite photo of my now divorced parents. It was taken in Hawaii in 1987 when they were competing in races and triathlons together.

My parents are runners.
My dad is a runner.
I am not a runner.

Because of my parents, I started running—and racing—when I was a child and ran well into college. I ran for 15 years. Running was always my dad’s thing, but I was never bad at it. So I ran too, despite never loving it the way he does.

Running eventually became punishment when I started to deal with body image and food issues in college. I started to run to lose weight when I was 21. This completely destroyed my relationship with it and I stopped. I only occasionally ran in WODs and short sprint workouts from then on.

I started running again for the first time in 10 years in December when I had no choice while at a 10-day WFR course. I was preparing for Cotopaxi with no way or time to train, so I ran 6-12 miles a day on a mix of dirt and pavement around the property.

I liked how it made my legs and lungs feel.
It felt like movement, not punishment.
I was reminded that I once ran for fun.
It made me feel connected to my dad.

So I started occasionally jogging the downhills on my hikes after then. Then I started occasionally jogging the flat parts too.

And about a month ago, I started going on hour long runs when it was too hot to do anything longer outside. Then bumped it up to 90 minutes this week.

I have no idea where this running thing is going or where it will end up. I have no expectations other than to have a healthy relationship with it.

All I know is that when I look at this picture of my 27 year old mom and 34 year old dad together at a race, I feel deeply connected to this version of them.

This picture tells me to run, so I am just going to keep running for the right reasons and see what happens.🏃🏼‍♀️

node.text:
I put the scale away and stopped weighing myself in May. I did this because—despite what many think—an increase in body weight doesn’t matter if performance and health aren’t suffering. (I will die on this hill).

I thought it would be better for my training brain if I was unaware of my weight for a while. And I was 100% correct. My climbing, hiking, lifting, and running all improved once I was entirely unaware of and unconcerned with my weight. Even when I knew I was likely gaining a little from eating more in order to train more.

I knew I was gaining throughout June for 2 reasons...
1️⃣ people started asking me if I was when I shared pictures of my body on here
2️⃣ my short liners and sports bras started to feel snugger by the week

But I stayed off the scale for nearly 6 weeks and didn’t view any of the above as bad. I kept doing what I was doing: eating lots and training hard. Because it works for me.

Then I was unexpectedly asked to step on a scale at the doctor’s office recently and couldn’t bring myself to not look…

Not only have I gained weight, but I’m also 1kg over my 72kg weight class from when I was a competitive powerlifter... as an endurance athlete.🤯

For years now, I have been told lighter is better when it comes to uphill and vertical sport. And have been told that I could be much better in all my sports if I was smaller.

Let me tell ya, I am so happy that I haven’t listened to any on these fucking people (all men) and have focussed on what matters rather than try to be smaller by eating less and not adequately fueling my body.

I started tracking my food and prioritizing my nutrition again this week for my own health. Rather than trying to lose the small amount of weight I’ve gained by restricting calories, I’m embracing it. Because this body is capable of some seriously rad shit right now and a few extra pounds aren’t weighing me down.

Be well ❤️🌮 (and think about staying off the damn scale)

Training video dump and wrap up from the week 🧗🏼‍♀️🏋🏼‍♀️🥾

I started leading 5.9, my lifts felt solid, and I got a good mix of both climbing and cardio in. Celiac disease and thunderstorms had other plans for us on Friday tho. So instead of a 13-15 hour car-to-car summit push in the mountains with busted guts and a looming storm, we stayed in Mammoth for the weekend and enjoyed some low stress climbing with friends. (Celiac disease sucks butt sometimes, I just try not to complain about it on here because people live with FAR worse).

Pretty mellow week of maintaining my current fitness level since I felt sick for a lot of it👇🏻

MON: AM-🏋🏼‍♀️ lifting / PM-🥾step-ups
TUE: AM-🚴🏼‍♀️ long stationary bike ride

FRI: PM- 🧗🏼‍♀️4h sport/trad climbing + hiking
SAT: 💎Crystal Crag climb (first video)
SUN: REST

The plan this week is to cook all my own food so my guts  are 100% for my next big adventure in a little over a week!

node.text:
What we dislike (and why) makes us just as interesting as what we like, in my opinion. So here are 10 random well-liked things I happen to strongly dislike (and why) to help you get to know me better—or decide you don’t like me and/or want to fight me should you take any of this personally 🤣😘
 
1️⃣ Halloween. I don’t like spooky anything, I don’t do costumes, and I don’t like scary decorations.
2️⃣ Country music. Unless it’s years older than me, I find it to be truly awful.
3️⃣ Disneyland. As an adult, it’s my hell on earth. An expensive place to wait in lines.
4️⃣ Motorcycles. Too loud and/or fast! I prefer slow, quiet danger.
5️⃣ Friends (the sitcom). Too cheesy and I can’t stand Ross. I prefer It’s Always Sunny.
6️⃣ The Bachelor/Bachelorette. No need to explain.
7️⃣ Licorice of any kind. It’s so bad! How do people eat it? I gag even thinking about it!
8️⃣ Scary movies of any kind. Why do people like being horrified and/or watching fucked up shit?
9️⃣ Caves, long tunnels, or anywhere else dark and snug that could kill me.
🔟 Music festivals. So. Many. People. Everywhere. And usually fucked up. This is the opposite of fun.

And there you have me in a nutshell!

Now tell me something well-liked that you don’t like👇🏻
